Declarations for @{b}rpcalc@{ub}
-----------------------

   Here are the C and Bison declarations for the reverse polish notation
calculator.  As in C, comments are placed between @{b}/*...*/@{ub}.

     /* Reverse polish notation calculator. */
     
     %{
     #define YYSTYPE double
     #include <math.h>
     %}
     
     %token NUM
     
     %% /* Grammar rules and actions follow */

   The C declarations section (see @{"The C Declarations Section" Link "C Declarations"}) contains
two preprocessor directives.

   The @{b}#define@{ub} directive defines the macro @{b}YYSTYPE@{ub}, thus specifying the
C data type for semantic values of both tokens and groupings (see
@{"Data Types of Semantic Values" Link "Value Type"}).  The Bison parser will use whatever type
@{b}YYSTYPE@{ub} is defined as; if you don't define it, @{b}int@{ub} is the default.
Because we specify @{b}double@{ub}, each token and each expression has an
associated value, which is a floating point number.

   The @{b}#include@{ub} directive is used to declare the exponentiation
function @{b}pow@{ub}.

   The second section, Bison declarations, provides information to
Bison about the token types (see @{"The Bison Declarations Section" Link "Bison Declarations"}).  Each
terminal symbol that is not a single-character literal must be declared
here.  (Single-character literals normally don't need to be declared.)
In this example, all the arithmetic operators are designated by
single-character literals, so the only terminal symbol that needs to be
declared is @{b}NUM@{ub}, the token type for numeric constants.


@EndNode

@Node "Rpcalc Rules" "Bison.guide/Rpcalc Rules"
@Next "Rpcalc Lexer"
@Prev "Rpcalc Decls"
@Toc "RPN Calc"

Grammar Rules for @{b}rpcalc@{ub}
------------------------

   Here are the grammar rules for the reverse polish notation
calculator.

     input:    /* empty */
             | input line
     ;
     
     line:     '\n'
             | exp '\n'  { printf ("\t%.10g\n", $1); }
     ;
     
     exp:      NUM             { $$ = $1;         }
             | exp exp '+'     { $$ = $1 + $2;    }
             | exp exp '-'     { $$ = $1 - $2;    }
             | exp exp '*'     { $$ = $1 * $2;    }
             | exp exp '/'     { $$ = $1 / $2;    }
           /* Exponentiation */
             | exp exp '^'     { $$ = pow ($1, $2); }
           /* Unary minus    */
             | exp 'n'         { $$ = -$1;        }
     ;
     %%

   The groupings of the rpcalc "language" defined here are the
expression (given the name @{b}exp@{ub}), the line of input (@{b}line@{ub}), and the
complete input transcript (@{b}input@{ub}).  Each of these nonterminal symbols
has several alternate rules, joined by the @{b}|@{ub} punctuator which is read
as "or".  The following sections explain what these rules mean.

   The semantics of the language is determined by the actions taken
when a grouping is recognized.  The actions are the C code that appears
inside braces.  See @{"Actions" Link "Actions"}.

   You must specify these actions in C, but Bison provides the means for
passing semantic values between the rules.  In each action, the
pseudo-variable @{b}$$@{ub} stands for the semantic value for the grouping that
the rule is going to construct.  Assigning a value to @{b}$$@{ub} is the main
job of most actions.  The semantic values of the components of the rule
are referred to as @{b}$1@{ub}, @{b}$2@{ub}, and so on.


 @{" Rpcalc Input " Link "Rpcalc Input"} 
 @{" Rpcalc Line " Link "Rpcalc Line"} 
 @{" Rpcalc Expr " Link "Rpcalc Expr"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Rpcalc Input" "Bison.guide/Rpcalc Input"
@Next "Rpcalc Line"
@Toc "Rpcalc Rules"

Explanation of @{b}input@{ub}
....................

   Consider the definition of @{b}input@{ub}:

     input:    /* empty */
             | input line
     ;

   This definition reads as follows: "A complete input is either an
empty string, or a complete input followed by an input line".  Notice
that "complete input" is defined in terms of itself.  This definition
is said to be @{i}left recursive@{ui} since @{b}input@{ub} appears always as the leftmost
symbol in the sequence.  See @{"Recursive Rules" Link "Recursion"}.

   The first alternative is empty because there are no symbols between
the colon and the first @{b}|@{ub}; this means that @{b}input@{ub} can match an empty
string of input (no tokens).  We write the rules this way because it is
legitimate to type @{b}Ctrl-d@{ub} right after you start the calculator.  It's
conventional to put an empty alternative first and write the comment @{b}/*
empty */@{ub} in it.

   The second alternate rule (@{b}input line@{ub}) handles all nontrivial input.
It means, "After reading any number of lines, read one more line if
possible."  The left recursion makes this rule into a loop.  Since the
first alternative matches empty input, the loop can be executed zero or
more times.

   The parser function @{b}yyparse@{ub} continues to process input until a
grammatical error is seen or the lexical analyzer says there are no more
input tokens; we will arrange for the latter to happen at end of file.


@EndNode

@Node "Rpcalc Line" "Bison.guide/Rpcalc Line"
@Next "Rpcalc Expr"
@Prev "Rpcalc Input"
@Toc "Rpcalc Rules"

Explanation of @{b}line@{ub}
...................

   Now consider the definition of @{b}line@{ub}:

     line:     '\n'
             | exp '\n'  { printf ("\t%.10g\n", $1); }
     ;

   The first alternative is a token which is a newline character; this
means that rpcalc accepts a blank line (and ignores it, since there is
no action).  The second alternative is an expression followed by a
newline.  This is the alternative that makes rpcalc useful.  The
semantic value of the @{b}exp@{ub} grouping is the value of @{b}$1@{ub} because the @{b}exp@{ub} in
question is the first symbol in the alternative.  The action prints this
value, which is the result of the computation the user asked for.

   This action is unusual because it does not assign a value to @{b}$$@{ub}.  As
a consequence, the semantic value associated with the @{b}line@{ub} is
uninitialized (its value will be unpredictable).  This would be a bug if
that value were ever used, but we don't use it: once rpcalc has printed
the value of the user's input line, that value is no longer needed.


@EndNode

@Node "Rpcalc Expr" "Bison.guide/Rpcalc Expr"
@Prev "Rpcalc Line"
@Toc "Rpcalc Rules"

Explanation of @{b}expr@{ub}
...................

   The @{b}exp@{ub} grouping has several rules, one for each kind of expression.
The first rule handles the simplest expressions: those that are just
numbers.  The second handles an addition-expression, which looks like
two expressions followed by a plus-sign.  The third handles
subtraction, and so on.

     exp:      NUM
             | exp exp '+'     { $$ = $1 + $2;    }
             | exp exp '-'     { $$ = $1 - $2;    }
             ...
             ;

   We have used @{b}|@{ub} to join all the rules for @{b}exp@{ub}, but we could equally
well have written them separately:

     exp:      NUM ;
     exp:      exp exp '+'     { $$ = $1 + $2;    } ;
     exp:      exp exp '-'     { $$ = $1 - $2;    } ;
             ...

   Most of the rules have actions that compute the value of the
expression in terms of the value of its parts.  For example, in the
rule for addition, @{b}$1@{ub} refers to the first component @{b}exp@{ub} and @{b}$2@{ub} refers to
the second one.  The third component, @{b}'+'@{ub}, has no meaningful associated
semantic value, but if it had one you could refer to it as @{b}$3@{ub}.  When
@{b}yyparse@{ub} recognizes a sum expression using this rule, the sum of the two
subexpressions' values is produced as the value of the entire
expression.  See @{"Actions" Link "Actions"}.

   You don't have to give an action for every rule.  When a rule has no
action, Bison by default copies the value of @{b}$1@{ub} into @{b}$$@{ub}.  This is what
happens in the first rule (the one that uses @{b}NUM@{ub}).

   The formatting shown here is the recommended convention, but Bison
does not require it.  You can add or change whitespace as much as you
wish.  For example, this:

     exp   : NUM | exp exp '+' {$$ = $1 + $2; } | ...

means the same thing as this:

     exp:      NUM
             | exp exp '+'    { $$ = $1 + $2; }
             | ...

The latter, however, is much more readable.


@EndNode

