The Error Reporting Routine
---------------------------

   When @{b}yyparse@{ub} detects a syntax error, it calls the error reporting
function @{b}yyerror@{ub} to print an error message (usually but not always
@{b}"parse error"@{ub}).  It is up to the programmer to supply @{b}yyerror@{ub} (see
@{"Parser C-Language Interface" Link "Interface"}), so here is the definition we will use:

     #include <stdio.h>
     
     yyerror (s)  /* Called by yyparse on error */
          char *s;
     {
       printf ("%s\n", s);
     }

   After @{b}yyerror@{ub} returns, the Bison parser may recover from the error
and continue parsing if the grammar contains a suitable error rule (see
@{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}).  Otherwise, @{b}yyparse@{ub} returns nonzero.  We have not
written any error rules in this example, so any invalid input will
cause the calculator program to exit.  This is not clean behavior for a
real calculator, but it is adequate in the first example.


@EndNode

