Running Bison to Make the Parser
--------------------------------

   Before running Bison to produce a parser, we need to decide how to
arrange all the source code in one or more source files.  For such a
simple example, the easiest thing is to put everything in one file.
The definitions of @{b}yylex@{ub}, @{b}yyerror@{ub} and @{b}main@{ub} go at the end, in the
"additional C code" section of the file (see
@{"The Overall Layout of a Bison Grammar" Link "Grammar Layout"}).

   For a large project, you would probably have several source files,
and use @{b}make@{ub} to arrange to recompile them.

   With all the source in a single file, you use the following command
to convert it into a parser file:

     bison @{i}file_name@{ui}.y

In this example the file was called @{b}rpcalc.y@{ub} (for "Reverse Polish
CALCulator").  Bison produces a file named @{b}@{i}file_name@{ui}.tab.c@{ub}, removing
the @{b}.y@{ub} from the original file name. The file output by Bison contains
the source code for @{b}yyparse@{ub}.  The additional functions in the input
file (@{b}yylex@{ub}, @{b}yyerror@{ub} and @{b}main@{ub}) are copied verbatim to the output.


@EndNode

