The C Declarations Section
--------------------------

   The @{i}C declarations@{ui} section contains macro definitions and
declarations of functions and variables that are used in the actions in
the grammar rules.  These are copied to the beginning of the parser
file so that they precede the definition of @{b}yyparse@{ub}.  You can use
@{b}#include@{ub} to get the declarations from a header file.  If you don't need
any C declarations, you may omit the @{b} %{@{ub} and @{b} %}@{ub} delimiters that
bracket this section.


@EndNode

@Node "Bison Declarations" "Bison.guide/Bison Declarations"
@Next "Grammar Rules"
@Prev "C Declarations"
@Toc "Grammar Outline"

The Bison Declarations Section
------------------------------

   The @{i}Bison declarations@{ui} section contains declarations that define
terminal and nonterminal symbols, specify precedence, and so on.  In
some simple grammars you may not need any declarations.  See
@{"Bison Declarations" Link "Declarations"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Grammar Rules" "Bison.guide/Grammar Rules"
@Next "C Code"
@Prev "Bison Declarations"
@Toc "Grammar Outline"

The Grammar Rules Section
-------------------------

   The @{i}grammar rules@{ui} section contains one or more Bison grammar rules,
and nothing else.  See @{"Syntax of Grammar Rules" Link "Rules"}.

   There must always be at least one grammar rule, and the first @{b}%%@{ub}
(which precedes the grammar rules) may never be omitted even if it is
the first thing in the file.


@EndNode

@Node "C Code" "Bison.guide/C Code"
@Prev "Grammar Rules"
@Toc "Grammar Outline"

The Additional C Code Section
-----------------------------

   The @{i}additional C code@{ui} section is copied verbatim to the end of the
parser file, just as the @{i}C declarations@{ui} section is copied to the
beginning.  This is the most convenient place to put anything that you
want to have in the parser file but which need not come before the
definition of @{b}yyparse@{ub}.  For example, the definitions of @{b}yylex@{ub} and
@{b}yyerror@{ub} often go here.  See @{"Parser C-Language Interface" Link "Interface"}.

   If the last section is empty, you may omit the @{b}%%@{ub} that separates it
from the grammar rules.

   The Bison parser itself contains many static variables whose names
start with @{b}yy@{ub} and many macros whose names start with @{b}YY@{ub}.  It is a good
idea to avoid using any such names (except those documented in this
manual) in the additional C code section of the grammar file.


@EndNode

@Node "Symbols" "Bison.guide/Symbols"
@Next "Rules"
@Prev "Grammar Outline"
@Toc "Grammar File"

Symbols, Terminal and Nonterminal
=================================

   @{i}Symbols@{ui} in Bison grammars represent the grammatical classifications
of the language.

   A @{i}terminal symbol@{ui} (also known as a @{i}token type@{ui}) represents a class of
syntactically equivalent tokens.  You use the symbol in grammar rules
to mean that a token in that class is allowed.  The symbol is
represented in the Bison parser by a numeric code, and the @{b}yylex@{ub}
function returns a token type code to indicate what kind of token has
been read.  You don't need to know what the code value is; you can use
the symbol to stand for it.

   A @{i}nonterminal symbol@{ui} stands for a class of syntactically equivalent
groupings.  The symbol name is used in writing grammar rules.  By
convention, it should be all lower case.

   Symbol names can contain letters, digits (not at the beginning),
underscores and periods.  Periods make sense only in nonterminals.

   There are two ways of writing terminal symbols in the grammar:

   @{b}*@{ub} A @{i}named token type@{ui} is written with an identifier, like an
     identifier in C.  By convention, it should be all upper case.  Each
     such name must be defined with a Bison declaration such as @{b}%token@{ub}.
     See @{"Token Type Names" Link "Token Decl"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} A @{i}character token type@{ui} (or @{i}literal token@{ui}) is written in the
     grammar using the same syntax used in C for character constants;
     for example, @{b}'+'@{ub} is a character token type.  A character token
     type doesn't need to be declared unless you need to specify its
     semantic value data type (see @{"Data Types of Semantic Values" Link "Value Type"}),
     associativity, or precedence (see @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence"}).

     By convention, a character token type is used only to represent a
     token that consists of that particular character.  Thus, the token
     type @{b}'+'@{ub} is used to represent the character @{b}+@{ub} as a token.  Nothing
     enforces this convention, but if you depart from it, your program
     will confuse other readers.

     All the usual escape sequences used in character literals in C can
     be used in Bison as well, but you must not use the null character
     as a character literal because its ASCII code, zero, is the code
     @{b}yylex@{ub} returns for end-of-input (see @{"Calling Convention for yylex" Link "Calling Convention"}).

   How you choose to write a terminal symbol has no effect on its
grammatical meaning.  That depends only on where it appears in rules and
on when the parser function returns that symbol.

   The value returned by @{b}yylex@{ub} is always one of the terminal symbols
(or 0 for end-of-input).  Whichever way you write the token type in the
grammar rules, you write it the same way in the definition of @{b}yylex@{ub}.
The numeric code for a character token type is simply the ASCII code for
the character, so @{b}yylex@{ub} can use the identical character constant to
generate the requisite code.  Each named token type becomes a C macro in
the parser file, so @{b}yylex@{ub} can use the name to stand for the code.
(This is why periods don't make sense in terminal symbols.) See
@{"Calling Convention for yylex" Link "Calling Convention"}.

   If @{b}yylex@{ub} is defined in a separate file, you need to arrange for the
token-type macro definitions to be available there.  Use the @{b}-d@{ub} option
when you run Bison, so that it will write these macro definitions into
a separate header file @{b}@{i}name@{ui}.tab.h@{ub} which you can include in the other
source files that need it.  See @{"Invoking Bison" Link "Invocation"}.

   The symbol @{b}error@{ub} is a terminal symbol reserved for error recovery
(see @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}); you shouldn't use it for any other purpose.  In
particular, @{b}yylex@{ub} should never return this value.


@EndNode

@Node "Rules" "Bison.guide/Rules"
@Next "Recursion"
@Prev "Symbols"
@Toc "Grammar File"

Syntax of Grammar Rules
=======================

   A Bison grammar rule has the following general form:

     @{i}result@{ui}: @{i}components@{ui} ...
             ;

where @{i}result@{ui} is the nonterminal symbol that this rule describes and
@{i}components@{ui} are various terminal and nonterminal symbols that are put
together by this rule (see @{"Symbols" Link "Symbols"}).

   For example,

     exp:      exp '+' exp
             ;

says that two groupings of type @{b}exp@{ub}, with a @{b}+@{ub} token in between, can be
combined into a larger grouping of type @{b}exp@{ub}.

   Whitespace in rules is significant only to separate symbols.  You
can add extra whitespace as you wish.

   Scattered among the components can be @{i}actions@{ui} that determine the
semantics of the rule.  An action looks like this:

     {@{i}C statements@{ui} }

Usually there is only one action and it follows the components.  See
@{"Actions" Link "Actions"}.

   Multiple rules for the same @{i}result@{ui} can be written separately or can
be joined with the vertical-bar character @{b}|@{ub} as follows:

     @{i}result@{ui}:   @{i}rule1-components@{ui} ...
             | @{i}rule2-components@{ui} ...
             ...
             ;

They are still considered distinct rules even when joined in this way.

   If @{i}components@{ui} in a rule is empty, it means that @{i}result@{ui} can match the
empty string.  For example, here is how to define a comma-separated
sequence of zero or more @{b}exp@{ub} groupings:

     expseq:   /* empty */
             | expseq1
             ;
     
     expseq1:  exp
             | expseq1 ',' exp
             ;

It is customary to write a comment @{b}/* empty */@{ub} in each rule with no
components.


@EndNode

@Node "Recursion" "Bison.guide/Recursion"
@Next "Semantics"
@Prev "Rules"
@Toc "Grammar File"

Recursive Rules
===============

   A rule is called @{i}recursive@{ui} when its @{i}result@{ui} nonterminal appears also
on its right hand side.  Nearly all Bison grammars need to use
recursion, because that is the only way to define a sequence of any
number of somethings.  Consider this recursive definition of a
comma-separated sequence of one or more expressions:

     expseq1:  exp
             | expseq1 ',' exp
             ;

Since the recursive use of @{b}expseq1@{ub} is the leftmost symbol in the right
hand side, we call this @{i}left recursion@{ui}.  By contrast, here the same
construct is defined using @{i}right recursion@{ui}:

     expseq1:  exp
             | exp ',' expseq1
             ;

Any kind of sequence can be defined using either left recursion or
right recursion, but you should always use left recursion, because it
can parse a sequence of any number of elements with bounded stack
space.  Right recursion uses up space on the Bison stack in proportion
to the number of elements in the sequence, because all the elements
must be shifted onto the stack before the rule can be applied even
once.  See @{"The Bison Parser Algorithm" Link "Algorithm"}, for further explanation of this.

   @{i}Indirect@{ui} or @{i}mutual@{ui} recursion occurs when the result of the rule does
not appear directly on its right hand side, but does appear in rules
for other nonterminals which do appear on its right hand side.

   For example:

     expr:     primary
             | primary '+' primary
             ;
     
     primary:  constant
             | '(' expr ')'
             ;

defines two mutually-recursive nonterminals, since each refers to the
other.


@EndNode

@Node "Semantics" "Bison.guide/Semantics"
@Next "Declarations"
@Prev "Recursion"
@Toc "Grammar File"

Defining Language Semantics
===========================

   The grammar rules for a language determine only the syntax.  The
semantics are determined by the semantic values associated with various
tokens and groupings, and by the actions taken when various groupings
are recognized.

   For example, the calculator calculates properly because the value
associated with each expression is the proper number; it adds properly
because the action for the grouping @{b}@{i}x@{ui} + @{i}y@{ui}@{ub} is to add the numbers
associated with @{i}x@{ui} and @{i}y@{ui}.


 @{" Value Type " Link "Value Type"}         Specifying one data type for all semantic values.
 @{" Multiple Types " Link "Multiple Types"}     Specifying several alternative data types.
 @{" Actions " Link "Actions"}            An action is the semantic definition of a grammar rule.
 @{" Action Types " Link "Action Types"}       Specifying data types for actions to operate on.
 @{" Mid-Rule Actions " Link "Mid-Rule Actions"}   Most actions go at the end of a rule.
                      This says when, why and how to use the exceptional
                        action in the middle of a rule.


@EndNode

@Node "Value Type" "Bison.guide/Value Type"
@Next "Multiple Types"
@Toc "Semantics"

Data Types of Semantic Values
-----------------------------

   In a simple program it may be sufficient to use the same data type
for the semantic values of all language constructs.  This was true in
the RPN and infix calculator examples (see
@{"Reverse Polish Notation Calculator" Link "RPN Calc"}).

   Bison's default is to use type @{b}int@{ub} for all semantic values.  To
specify some other type, define @{b}YYSTYPE@{ub} as a macro, like this:

     #define YYSTYPE double

This macro definition must go in the C declarations section of the
grammar file (see @{"Outline of a Bison Grammar" Link "Grammar Outline"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Multiple Types" "Bison.guide/Multiple Types"
@Next "Actions"
@Prev "Value Type"
@Toc "Semantics"

More Than One Value Type
------------------------

   In most programs, you will need different data types for different
kinds of tokens and groupings.  For example, a numeric constant may
need type @{b}int@{ub} or @{b}long@{ub}, while a string constant needs type @{b}char *@{ub}, and
an identifier might need a pointer to an entry in the symbol table.

   To use more than one data type for semantic values in one parser,
Bison requires you to do two things:

   @{b}*@{ub} Specify the entire collection of possible data types, with the
     @{b}%union@{ub} Bison declaration (see @{"The Collection of Value Types" Link "Union Decl"}).

   @{b}*@{ub} Choose one of those types for each symbol (terminal or nonterminal)
     for which semantic values are used.  This is done for tokens with
     the @{b}%token@{ub} Bison declaration (see @{"Token Type Names" Link "Token Decl"}) and for
     groupings with the @{b}%type@{ub} Bison declaration (see
     @{"Nonterminal Symbols" Link "Type Decl"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Actions" "Bison.guide/Actions"
@Next "Action Types"
@Prev "Multiple Types"
@Toc "Semantics"

Actions
-------

   An action accompanies a syntactic rule and contains C code to be
executed each time an instance of that rule is recognized.  The task of
most actions is to compute a semantic value for the grouping built by
the rule from the semantic values associated with tokens or smaller
groupings.

   An action consists of C statements surrounded by braces, much like a
compound statement in C.  It can be placed at any position in the rule;
it is executed at that position.  Most rules have just one action at
the end of the rule, following all the components.  Actions in the
middle of a rule are tricky and used only for special purposes (see
@{"Actions in Mid-Rule" Link "Mid-Rule Actions"}).

   The C code in an action can refer to the semantic values of the
components matched by the rule with the construct @{b} $@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}, which stands for
the value of the @{i}n@{ui}th component.  The semantic value for the grouping
being constructed is @{b}$$@{ub}.  (Bison translates both of these constructs
into array element references when it copies the actions into the parser
file.)

   Here is a typical example:

     exp:    ...
             | exp '+' exp
                 { $$ = $1 + $3; }

This rule constructs an @{b}exp@{ub} from two smaller @{b}exp@{ub} groupings connected by
a plus-sign token.  In the action, @{b}$1@{ub} and @{b}$3@{ub} refer to the semantic
values of the two component @{b}exp@{ub} groupings, which are the first and
third symbols on the right hand side of the rule.  The sum is stored
into @{b}$$@{ub} so that it becomes the semantic value of the
addition-expression just recognized by the rule.  If there were a
useful semantic value associated with the @{b}+@{ub} token, it could be referred
to as @{b}$2@{ub}.

   If you don't specify an action for a rule, Bison supplies a default:
@{b}$$ = $1@{ub}.  Thus, the value of the first symbol in the rule becomes the
value of the whole rule.  Of course, the default rule is valid only if
the two data types match.  There is no meaningful default action for an
empty rule; every empty rule must have an explicit action unless the
rule's value does not matter.

   @{b} $@{i}n@{ui}@{ub} with @{i}n@{ui} zero or negative is allowed for reference to tokens and
groupings on the stack @{i}before@{ui} those that match the current rule.  This
is a very risky practice, and to use it reliably you must be certain of
the context in which the rule is applied.  Here is a case in which you
can use this reliably:

     foo:      expr bar '+' expr  { ... }
             | expr bar '-' expr  { ... }
             ;
     
     bar:      /* empty */
             { previous_expr = $0; }
             ;

   As long as @{b}bar@{ub} is used only in the fashion shown here, @{b}$0@{ub} always
refers to the @{b}expr@{ub} which precedes @{b}bar@{ub} in the definition of @{b}foo@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Action Types" "Bison.guide/Action Types"
@Next "Mid-Rule Actions"
@Prev "Actions"
@Toc "Semantics"

Data Types of Values in Actions
-------------------------------

   If you have chosen a single data type for semantic values, the @{b}$$@{ub}
and @{b} $@{i}n@{ui}@{ub} constructs always have that data type.

   If you have used @{b}%union@{ub} to specify a variety of data types, then you
must declare a choice among these types for each terminal or nonterminal
symbol that can have a semantic value.  Then each time you use @{b}$$@{ub} or @{b}
$@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}, its data type is determined by which symbol it refers
to in the rule.  In this example,

     exp:    ...
             | exp '+' exp
                 { $$ = $1 + $3; }

@{b}$1@{ub} and @{b}$3@{ub} refer to instances of @{b}exp@{ub}, so they all have the data type
declared for the nonterminal symbol @{b}exp@{ub}.  If @{b}$2@{ub} were used, it would
have the data type declared for the terminal symbol @{b}'+'@{ub}, whatever that
might be.

   Alternatively, you can specify the data type when you refer to the
value, by inserting @{b} <@{i}type@{ui}>@{ub} after the @{b}$@{ub} at the beginning of the
reference.  For example, if you have defined types as shown here:

     %union {
       int itype;
       double dtype;
     }

then you can write @{b}$<itype>1@{ub} to refer to the first subunit of the rule
as an integer, or @{b}$<dtype>1@{ub} to refer to it as a double.


@EndNode

@Node "Mid-Rule Actions" "Bison.guide/Mid-Rule Actions"
@Prev "Action Types"
@Toc "Semantics"

Actions in Mid-Rule
-------------------

   Occasionally it is useful to put an action in the middle of a rule.
These actions are written just like usual end-of-rule actions, but they
are executed before the parser even recognizes the following components.

   A mid-rule action may refer to the components preceding it using @{b}
$@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}, but it may not refer to subsequent components because
it is run before they are parsed.

   The mid-rule action itself counts as one of the components of the
rule.  This makes a difference when there is another action later in
the same rule (and usually there is another at the end): you have to
count the actions along with the symbols when working out which number
@{i}n@{ui} to use in @{b} $@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}.

   The mid-rule action can also have a semantic value.  The action can
set its value with an assignment to @{b}$$@{ub}, and actions later in the rule
can refer to the value using @{b} $@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}.  Since there is no symbol to name the
action, there is no way to declare a data type for the value in
advance, so you must use the @{b}$<...>@{ub} construct to specify a data type
each time you refer to this value.

   There is no way to set the value of the entire rule with a mid-rule
action, because assignments to @{b}$$@{ub} do not have that effect.  The only
way to set the value for the entire rule is with an ordinary action at
the end of the rule.

   Here is an example from a hypothetical compiler, handling a @{b}let@{ub}
statement that looks like @{b}let (@{i}variable@{ui}) @{i}statement@{ui}@{ub} and serves to create
a variable named @{i}variable@{ui} temporarily for the duration of @{i}statement@{ui}.
To parse this construct, we must put @{i}variable@{ui} into the symbol table
while @{i}statement@{ui} is parsed, then remove it afterward.  Here is how it is
done:

     stmt:   LET '(' var ')'
                     { $<context>$ = push_context ();
                       declare_variable ($3); }
             stmt    { $$ = $6;
                       pop_context ($<context>5); }

As soon as @{b}let (@{i}variable@{ui})@{ub} has been recognized, the first action is run.
It saves a copy of the current semantic context (the list of
accessible variables) as its semantic value, using alternative @{b}context@{ub}
in the data-type union.  Then it calls @{b}declare_variable@{ub} to add the new
variable to that list.  Once the first action is finished, the embedded
statement @{b}stmt@{ub} can be parsed.  Note that the mid-rule action is
component number 5, so the @{b}stmt@{ub} is component number 6.

   After the embedded statement is parsed, its semantic value becomes
the value of the entire @{b}let@{ub}-statement.  Then the semantic value from the
earlier action is used to restore the prior list of variables.  This
removes the temporary @{b}let@{ub}-variable from the list so that it won't
appear to exist while the rest of the program is parsed.

   Taking action before a rule is completely recognized often leads to
conflicts since the parser must commit to a parse in order to execute
the action.  For example, the following two rules, without mid-rule
actions, can coexist in a working parser because the parser can shift
the open-brace token and look at what follows before deciding whether
there is a declaration or not:

     compound: '{' declarations statements '}'
             | '{' statements '}'
             ;

But when we add a mid-rule action as follows, the rules become
nonfunctional:

     compound: { prepare_for_local_variables (); }
               '{' declarations statements '}'
             | '{' statements '}'
             ;

Now the parser is forced to decide whether to run the mid-rule action
when it has read no farther than the open-brace.  In other words, it
must commit to using one rule or the other, without sufficient
information to do it correctly.  (The open-brace token is what is called
the @{i}look-ahead@{ui} token at this time, since the parser is still deciding
what to do about it.  See @{"Look-Ahead Tokens" Link "Look-Ahead"}.)

   You might think that you could correct the problem by putting
identical actions into the two rules, like this:

     compound: { prepare_for_local_variables (); }
               '{' declarations statements '}'
             | { prepare_for_local_variables (); }
               '{' statements '}'
             ;

But this does not help, because Bison does not realize that the two
actions are identical.  (Bison never tries to understand the C code in
an action.)

   If the grammar is such that a declaration can be distinguished from a
statement by the first token (which is true in C), then one solution
which does work is to put the action after the open-brace, like this:

     compound: '{' { prepare_for_local_variables (); }
               declarations statements '}'
             | '{' statements '}'
             ;

Now the first token of the following declaration or statement, which
would in any case tell Bison which rule to use, can still do so.

   Another solution is to bury the action inside a nonterminal symbol
which serves as a subroutine:

     subroutine: /* empty */
               { prepare_for_local_variables (); }
             ;
     
     compound: subroutine
               '{' declarations statements '}'
             | subroutine
               '{' statements '}'
             ;

Now Bison can execute the action in the rule for @{b}subroutine@{ub} without
deciding which rule for @{b}compound@{ub} it will eventually use.  Note that the
action is now at the end of its rule.  Any mid-rule action can be
converted to an end-of-rule action in this way, and this is what Bison
actually does to implement mid-rule actions.


@EndNode

@Node "Declarations" "Bison.guide/Declarations"
@Next "Multiple Parsers"
@Prev "Semantics"
@Toc "Grammar File"

Bison Declarations
==================

   The @{i}Bison declarations@{ui} section of a Bison grammar defines the symbols
used in formulating the grammar and the data types of semantic values.
See @{"Symbols" Link "Symbols"}.

   All token type names (but not single-character literal tokens such as
@{b}'+'@{ub} and @{b}'*'@{ub}) must be declared.  Nonterminal symbols must be declared if
you need to specify which data type to use for the semantic value (see
@{"More Than One Value Type" Link "Multiple Types"}).

   The first rule in the file also specifies the start symbol, by
default.  If you want some other symbol to be the start symbol, you
must declare it explicitly (see @{"Languages and Context-Free Grammars" Link "Language and Grammar"}).


 @{" Token Decl " Link "Token Decl"}         Declaring terminal symbols.
 @{" Precedence Decl " Link "Precedence Decl"}    Declaring terminals with precedence and associativity.
 @{" Union Decl " Link "Union Decl"}         Declaring the set of all semantic value types.
 @{" Type Decl " Link "Type Decl"}          Declaring the choice of type for a nonterminal symbol.
 @{" Expect Decl " Link "Expect Decl"}        Suppressing warnings about shift/reduce conflicts.
 @{" Start Decl " Link "Start Decl"}         Specifying the start symbol.
 @{" Pure Decl " Link "Pure Decl"}          Requesting a reentrant parser.
 @{" Decl Summary " Link "Decl Summary"}       Table of all Bison declarations.


@EndNode

@Node "Token Decl" "Bison.guide/Token Decl"
@Next "Precedence Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

Token Type Names
----------------

   The basic way to declare a token type name (terminal symbol) is as
follows:

     %token @{i}name@{ui}

   Bison will convert this into a @{b}#define@{ub} directive in the parser, so
that the function @{b}yylex@{ub} (if it is in this file) can use the name @{i}name@{ui}
to stand for this token type's code.

   Alternatively, you can use @{b}%left@{ub}, @{b}%right@{ub}, or @{b}%nonassoc@{ub} instead of
@{b}%token@{ub}, if you wish to specify precedence.  See @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence Decl"}.

   You can explicitly specify the numeric code for a token type by
appending an integer value in the field immediately following the token
name:

     %token NUM 300

It is generally best, however, to let Bison choose the numeric codes for
all token types.  Bison will automatically select codes that don't
conflict with each other or with ASCII characters.

   In the event that the stack type is a union, you must augment the
@{b}%token@{ub} or other token declaration to include the data type alternative
delimited by angle-brackets (see @{"More Than One Value Type" Link "Multiple Types"}).

   For example:

     %union {              /* define stack type */
       double val;
       symrec *tptr;
     }
     %token <val> NUM      /* define token NUM and its type */


@EndNode

@Node "Precedence Decl" "Bison.guide/Precedence Decl"
@Next "Union Decl"
@Prev "Token Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

Operator Precedence
-------------------

   Use the @{b}%left@{ub}, @{b}%right@{ub} or @{b}%nonassoc@{ub} declaration to declare a token
and specify its precedence and associativity, all at once.  These are
called @{i}precedence declarations@{ui}.  See @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence"}, for general
information on operator precedence.

   The syntax of a precedence declaration is the same as that of
@{b}%token@{ub}: either

     %left @{i}symbols@{ui} ...

or

     %left <@{i}type@{ui}> @{i}symbols@{ui} ...

   And indeed any of these declarations serves the purposes of @{b}%token@{ub}.
But in addition, they specify the associativity and relative precedence
for all the @{i}symbols@{ui}:

   @{b}*@{ub} The associativity of an operator @{i}op@{ui} determines how repeated uses
     of the operator nest: whether @{b}@{i}x@{ui} @{i}op@{ui} @{i}y@{ui} @{i}op@{ui} @{i}z@{ui}@{ub} is parsed by grouping @{i}x@{ui}
     with @{i}y@{ui} first or by grouping @{i}y@{ui} with @{i}z@{ui} first.  @{b}%left@{ub} specifies
     left-associativity (grouping @{i}x@{ui} with @{i}y@{ui} first) and @{b}%right@{ub} specifies
     right-associativity (grouping @{i}y@{ui} with @{i}z@{ui} first).  @{b}%nonassoc@{ub}
     specifies no associativity, which means that @{b}@{i}x@{ui} @{i}op@{ui} @{i}y@{ui} @{i}op@{ui} @{i}z@{ui}@{ub} is
     considered a syntax error.

   @{b}*@{ub} The precedence of an operator determines how it nests with other
     operators.  All the tokens declared in a single precedence
     declaration have equal precedence and nest together according to
     their associativity.  When two tokens declared in different
     precedence declarations associate, the one declared later has the
     higher precedence and is grouped first.


@EndNode

@Node "Union Decl" "Bison.guide/Union Decl"
@Next "Type Decl"
@Prev "Precedence Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

The Collection of Value Types
-----------------------------

   The @{b}%union@{ub} declaration specifies the entire collection of possible
data types for semantic values.  The keyword @{b}%union@{ub} is followed by a
pair of braces containing the same thing that goes inside a @{b}union@{ub} in C.

   For example:

     %union {
       double val;
       symrec *tptr;
     }

This says that the two alternative types are @{b}double@{ub} and @{b}symrec *@{ub}.  They
are given names @{b}val@{ub} and @{b}tptr@{ub}; these names are used in the @{b}%token@{ub} and
@{b}%type@{ub} declarations to pick one of the types for a terminal or
nonterminal symbol (see @{"Nonterminal Symbols" Link "Type Decl"}).

   Note that, unlike making a @{b}union@{ub} declaration in C, you do not write
a semicolon after the closing brace.


@EndNode

@Node "Type Decl" "Bison.guide/Type Decl"
@Next "Expect Decl"
@Prev "Union Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

Nonterminal Symbols
-------------------

When you use @{b}%union@{ub} to specify multiple value types, you must declare
the value type of each nonterminal symbol for which values are used.
This is done with a @{b}%type@{ub} declaration, like this:

     %type <@{i}type@{ui}> @{i}nonterminal@{ui} ...

Here @{i}nonterminal@{ui} is the name of a nonterminal symbol, and @{i}type@{ui} is the
name given in the @{b}%union@{ub} to the alternative that you want (see
@{"The Collection of Value Types" Link "Union Decl"}).  You can give any number of nonterminal
symbols in the same @{b}%type@{ub} declaration, if they have the same value
type.  Use spaces to separate the symbol names.


@EndNode

@Node "Expect Decl" "Bison.guide/Expect Decl"
@Next "Start Decl"
@Prev "Type Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

Suppressing Conflict Warnings
-----------------------------

   Bison normally warns if there are any conflicts in the grammar (see
@{"Shift/Reduce Conflicts" Link "Shift-Reduce"}), but most real grammars have harmless
shift/reduce conflicts which are resolved in a predictable way and
would be difficult to eliminate.  It is desirable to suppress the
warning about these conflicts unless the number of conflicts changes.
You can do this with the @{b}%expect@{ub} declaration.

   The declaration looks like this:

     %expect @{i}n@{ui}

   Here @{i}n@{ui} is a decimal integer.  The declaration says there should be no
warning if there are @{i}n@{ui} shift/reduce conflicts and no reduce/reduce
conflicts.  The usual warning is given if there are either more or fewer
conflicts, or if there are any reduce/reduce conflicts.

   In general, using @{b}%expect@{ub} involves these steps:

   @{b}*@{ub} Compile your grammar without @{b}%expect@{ub}.  Use the @{b}-v@{ub} option to get a
     verbose list of where the conflicts occur.  Bison will also print
     the number of conflicts.

   @{b}*@{ub} Check each of the conflicts to make sure that Bison's default
     resolution is what you really want.  If not, rewrite the grammar
     and go back to the beginning.

   @{b}*@{ub} Add an @{b}%expect@{ub} declaration, copying the number @{i}n@{ui} from the number
     which Bison printed.

   Now Bison will stop annoying you about the conflicts you have
checked, but it will warn you again if changes in the grammar result in
additional conflicts.


@EndNode

@Node "Start Decl" "Bison.guide/Start Decl"
@Next "Pure Decl"
@Prev "Expect Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

The Start-Symbol
----------------

   Bison assumes by default that the start symbol for the grammar is
the first nonterminal specified in the grammar specification section.
The programmer may override this restriction with the @{b}%start@{ub}
declaration as follows:

     %start @{i}symbol@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "Pure Decl" "Bison.guide/Pure Decl"
@Next "Decl Summary"
@Prev "Start Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

A Pure (Reentrant) Parser
-------------------------

   A @{i}reentrant@{ui} program is one which does not alter in the course of
execution; in other words, it consists entirely of @{i}pure@{ui} (read-only)
code.  Reentrancy is important whenever asynchronous execution is
possible; for example, a nonreentrant program may not be safe to call
from a signal handler.  In systems with multiple threads of control, a
nonreentrant program must be called only within interlocks.

   The Bison parser is not normally a reentrant program, because it uses
statically allocated variables for communication with @{b}yylex@{ub}.  These
variables include @{b}yylval@{ub} and @{b}yylloc@{ub}.

   The Bison declaration @{b}%pure_parser@{ub} says that you want the parser to
be reentrant.  It looks like this:

     %pure_parser

   The effect is that the two communication variables become local
variables in @{b}yyparse@{ub}, and a different calling convention is used for
the lexical analyzer function @{b}yylex@{ub}.  See
@{"Calling Conventions for Pure Parsers" Link "Pure Calling"}, for the details of this.  The
variable @{b}yynerrs@{ub} also becomes local in @{b}yyparse@{ub} (see
@{"The Error Reporting Function yyerror" Link "Error Reporting"}).  The convention for calling
@{b}yyparse@{ub} itself is unchanged.


@EndNode

@Node "Decl Summary" "Bison.guide/Decl Summary"
@Prev "Pure Decl"
@Toc "Declarations"

Bison Declaration Summary
-------------------------

   Here is a summary of all Bison declarations:

@{b}%union@{ub}
     Declare the collection of data types that semantic values may have
     (see @{"The Collection of Value Types" Link "Union Decl"}).

@{b}%token@{ub}
     Declare a terminal symbol (token type name) with no precedence or
     associativity specified (see @{"Token Type Names" Link "Token Decl"}).

@{b}%right@{ub}
     Declare a terminal symbol (token type name) that is
     right-associative (see @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence Decl"}).

@{b}%left@{ub}
     Declare a terminal symbol (token type name) that is
     left-associative (see @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence Decl"}).

@{b}%nonassoc@{ub}
     Declare a terminal symbol (token type name) that is nonassociative
     (using it in a way that would be associative is a syntax error)
     (see @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence Decl"}).

@{b}%type@{ub}
     Declare the type of semantic values for a nonterminal symbol (see
     @{"Nonterminal Symbols" Link "Type Decl"}).

@{b}%start@{ub}
     Specify the grammar's start symbol (see @{"The Start-Symbol" Link "Start Decl"}).

@{b}%expect@{ub}
     Declare the expected number of shift-reduce conflicts (see
     @{"Suppressing Conflict Warnings" Link "Expect Decl"}).

@{b}%pure_parser@{ub}
     Request a pure (reentrant) parser program (see
     @{"A Pure (Reentrant) Parser" Link "Pure Decl"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Multiple Parsers" "Bison.guide/Multiple Parsers"
@Prev "Declarations"
@Toc "Grammar File"

Multiple Parsers in the Same Program
====================================

   Most programs that use Bison parse only one language and therefore
contain only one Bison parser.  But what if you want to parse more than
one language with the same program?  Then you need to avoid a name
conflict between different definitions of @{b}yyparse@{ub}, @{b}yylval@{ub}, and so on.

   The easy way to do this is to use the option @{b}-p @{i}prefix@{ui}@{ub} (see
@{"Invoking Bison" Link "Invocation"}).  This renames the interface functions and variables of
the Bison parser to start with @{i}prefix@{ui} instead of @{b}yy@{ub}.  You can use this
to give each parser distinct names that do not conflict.

   The precise list of symbols renamed is @{b}yyparse@{ub}, @{b}yylex@{ub}, @{b}yyerror@{ub},
@{b}yynerrs@{ub}, @{b}yylval@{ub}, @{b}yychar@{ub} and @{b}yydebug@{ub}.  For example, if you use @{b}-p c@{ub}, the
names become @{b}cparse@{ub}, @{b}clex@{ub}, and so on.

   @{i}All the other variables and macros associated with Bison are not
renamed.@{ui} These others are not global; there is no conflict if the same
name is used in different parsers.  For example, @{b}YYSTYPE@{ub} is not
renamed, but defining this in different ways in different parsers causes
no trouble (see @{"Data Types of Semantic Values" Link "Value Type"}).

   The @{b}-p@{ub} option works by adding macro definitions to the beginning of
the parser source file, defining @{b}yyparse@{ub} as @{b}@{i}prefix@{ui}parse@{ub}, and so on.
This effectively substitutes one name for the other in the entire
parser file.


@EndNode

@Node "Interface" "Bison.guide/Interface"
@Next "Algorithm"
@Prev "Grammar File"
@Toc "Main"

Parser C-Language Interface
***************************

   The Bison parser is actually a C function named @{b}yyparse@{ub}.  Here we
describe the interface conventions of @{b}yyparse@{ub} and the other functions
that it needs to use.

   Keep in mind that the parser uses many C identifiers starting with
@{b}yy@{ub} and @{b}YY@{ub} for internal purposes.  If you use such an identifier
(aside from those in this manual) in an action or in additional C code
in the grammar file, you are likely to run into trouble.


 @{" Parser Function " Link "Parser Function"}    How to call @{b}yyparse@{ub} and what it returns.
 @{" Lexical " Link "Lexical"}            You must supply a function @{b}yylex@{ub}
                        which reads tokens.
 @{" Error Reporting " Link "Error Reporting"}    You must supply a function @{b}yyerror@{ub}.
 @{" Action Features " Link "Action Features"}    Special features for use in actions.


@EndNode

@Node "Parser Function" "Bison.guide/Parser Function"
@Next "Lexical"
@Toc "Interface"

The Parser Function @{b}yyparse@{ub}
===========================

   You call the function @{b}yyparse@{ub} to cause parsing to occur.  This
function reads tokens, executes actions, and ultimately returns when it
encounters end-of-input or an unrecoverable syntax error.  You can also
write an action which directs @{b}yyparse@{ub} to return immediately without
reading further.

   The value returned by @{b}yyparse@{ub} is 0 if parsing was successful (return
is due to end-of-input).

   The value is 1 if parsing failed (return is due to a syntax error).

   In an action, you can cause immediate return from @{b}yyparse@{ub} by using
these macros:

@{b}YYACCEPT@{ub}
     Return immediately with value 0 (to report success).

@{b}YYABORT@{ub}
     Return immediately with value 1 (to report failure).


@EndNode

@Node "Lexical" "Bison.guide/Lexical"
@Next "Error Reporting"
@Prev "Parser Function"
@Toc "Interface"

The Lexical Analyzer Function @{b}yylex@{ub}
===================================

   The @{i}lexical analyzer@{ui} function, @{b}yylex@{ub}, recognizes tokens from the
input stream and returns them to the parser.  Bison does not create
this function automatically; you must write it so that @{b}yyparse@{ub} can call
it.  The function is sometimes referred to as a lexical scanner.

   In simple programs, @{b}yylex@{ub} is often defined at the end of the Bison
grammar file.  If @{b}yylex@{ub} is defined in a separate source file, you need
to arrange for the token-type macro definitions to be available there.
To do this, use the @{b}-d@{ub} option when you run Bison, so that it will write
these macro definitions into a separate header file @{b}@{i}name@{ui}.tab.h@{ub} which
you can include in the other source files that need it.  See
@{"Invoking Bison" Link "Invocation"}.


 @{" Calling Convention " Link "Calling Convention"}   How @{b}yyparse@{ub} calls @{b}yylex@{ub}.
 @{" Token Values " Link "Token Values"}       How @{b}yylex@{ub} must return the semantic value
                        of the token it has read.
 @{" Token Positions " Link "Token Positions"}    How @{b}yylex@{ub} must return the text position
                        (line number, etc.) of the token, if the
                        actions want that.
 @{" Pure Calling " Link "Pure Calling"}       How the calling convention differs
                        in a pure parser (see @{"A Pure (Reentrant) Parser" Link "Pure Decl"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Calling Convention" "Bison.guide/Calling Convention"
@Next "Token Values"
@Toc "Lexical"

Calling Convention for @{b}yylex@{ub}
----------------------------

   The value that @{b}yylex@{ub} returns must be the numeric code for the type
of token it has just found, or 0 for end-of-input.

   When a token is referred to in the grammar rules by a name, that name
in the parser file becomes a C macro whose definition is the proper
numeric code for that token type.  So @{b}yylex@{ub} can use the name to
indicate that type.  See @{"Symbols" Link "Symbols"}.

   When a token is referred to in the grammar rules by a character
literal, the numeric code for that character is also the code for the
token type.  So @{b}yylex@{ub} can simply return that character code.  The null
character must not be used this way, because its code is zero and that
is what signifies end-of-input.

   Here is an example showing these things:

     yylex ()
     {
       ...
       if (c == EOF)     /* Detect end of file. */
         return 0;
       ...
       if (c == '+' || c == '-')
         return c;      /* Assume token type for `+' is '+'. */
       ...
       return INT;      /* Return the type of the token. */
       ...
     }

This interface has been designed so that the output from the @{b}lex@{ub}
utility can be used without change as the definition of @{b}yylex@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Token Values" "Bison.guide/Token Values"
@Next "Token Positions"
@Prev "Calling Convention"
@Toc "Lexical"

Semantic Values of Tokens
-------------------------

   In an ordinary (nonreentrant) parser, the semantic value of the
token must be stored into the global variable @{b}yylval@{ub}.  When you are
using just one data type for semantic values, @{b}yylval@{ub} has that type.
Thus, if the type is @{b}int@{ub} (the default), you might write this in @{b}yylex@{ub}:

       ...
       yylval = value;  /* Put value onto Bison stack. */
       return INT;      /* Return the type of the token. */
       ...

   When you are using multiple data types, @{b}yylval@{ub}'s type is a union
made from the @{b}%union@{ub} declaration (see @{"The Collection of Value Types" Link "Union Decl"}).
So when you store a token's value, you must use the proper member of
the union.  If the @{b}%union@{ub} declaration looks like this:

     %union {
       int intval;
       double val;
       symrec *tptr;
     }

then the code in @{b}yylex@{ub} might look like this:

       ...
       yylval.intval = value; /* Put value onto Bison stack. */
       return INT;          /* Return the type of the token. */
       ...


@EndNode

@Node "Token Positions" "Bison.guide/Token Positions"
@Next "Pure Calling"
@Prev "Token Values"
@Toc "Lexical"

Textual Positions of Tokens
---------------------------

   If you are using the @{b} @@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}-feature (see
@{"Special Features for Use in Actions" Link "Action Features"}) in actions to keep track of the
textual locations of tokens and groupings, then you must provide this
information in @{b}yylex@{ub}.  The function @{b}yyparse@{ub} expects to find the textual
location of a token just parsed in the global variable @{b}yylloc@{ub}.  So
@{b}yylex@{ub} must store the proper data in that variable.  The value of
@{b}yylloc@{ub} is a structure and you need only initialize the members that are
going to be used by the actions.  The four members are called
@{b}first_line@{ub}, @{b}first_column@{ub}, @{b}last_line@{ub} and @{b}last_column@{ub}.  Note that the
use of this feature makes the parser noticeably slower.

   The data type of @{b}yylloc@{ub} has the name @{b}YYLTYPE@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Pure Calling" "Bison.guide/Pure Calling"
@Prev "Token Positions"
@Toc "Lexical"

Calling Conventions for Pure Parsers
------------------------------------

   When you use the Bison declaration @{b}%pure_parser@{ub} to request a pure,
reentrant parser, the global communication variables @{b}yylval@{ub} and @{b}yylloc@{ub}
cannot be used.  (See @{"A Pure (Reentrant) Parser" Link "Pure Decl"}.)  In such parsers the
two global variables are replaced by pointers passed as arguments to
@{b}yylex@{ub}.  You must declare them as shown here, and pass the information
back by storing it through those pointers.

     yylex (lvalp, llocp)
          YYSTYPE *lvalp;
          YYLTYPE *llocp;
     {
       ...
       *lvalp = value;  /* Put value onto Bison stack.  */
       return INT;      /* Return the type of the token.  */
       ...
     }

   If the grammar file does not use the @{b} @@{ub} constructs to refer to
textual positions, then the type @{b}YYLTYPE@{ub} will not be defined.  In this
case, omit the second argument; @{b}yylex@{ub} will be called with only one
argument.

   You can pass parameter information to a reentrant parser in a
reentrant way.  Define the macro @{b}YYPARSE_PARAM@{ub} as a variable name.  The
resulting @{b}yyparse@{ub} function then accepts one argument, of type @{b}void *@{ub},
with that name.

   When you call @{b}yyparse@{ub}, pass the address of an object, casting the
address to @{b}void *@{ub}.  The grammar actions can refer to the contents of
the object by casting the pointer value back to its proper type and
then dereferencing it.  Here's an example.  Write this in the parser:

     %{
     struct parser_control
     {
       int nastiness;
       int randomness;
     };
     
     #define YYPARSE_PARAM parm
     %}

Then call the parser like this:

     struct parser_control
     {
       int nastiness;
       int randomness;
     };
     
     ...
     
     {
       struct parser_control foo;
       ...  /* Store proper data in @{b}foo@{ub}.  */
       value = yyparse ((void *) &foo);
       ...
     }

In the grammar actions, use expressions like this to refer to the data:

     ((struct parser_control *) parm)->randomness

   If you wish to pass the additional parameter data to @{b}yylex@{ub}, define
the macro @{b}YYLEX_PARAM@{ub} just like @{b}YYPARSE_PARAM@{ub}, as shown here:

     %{
     struct parser_control
     {
       int nastiness;
       int randomness;
     };
     
     #define YYPARSE_PARAM parm
     #define YYLEX_PARAM parm
     %}

   You should then define @{b}yylex@{ub} to accept one additional argument--the
value of @{b}parm@{ub}.  (This makes either two or three arguments in total,
depending on whether an argument of type @{b}YYLTYPE@{ub} is passed.)  You can
declare the argument as a pointer to the proper object type, or you can
declare it as @{b}void *@{ub} and access the contents as shown above.


@EndNode

@Node "Error Reporting" "Bison.guide/Error Reporting"
@Next "Action Features"
@Prev "Lexical"
@Toc "Interface"

The Error Reporting Function @{b}yyerror@{ub}
====================================

   The Bison parser detects a @{i}parse error@{ui} or @{i}syntax error@{ui} whenever it
reads a token which cannot satisfy any syntax rule.  A action in the
grammar can also explicitly proclaim an error, using the macro @{b}YYERROR@{ub}
(see @{"Special Features for Use in Actions" Link "Action Features"}).

   The Bison parser expects to report the error by calling an error
reporting function named @{b}yyerror@{ub}, which you must supply.  It is called
by @{b}yyparse@{ub} whenever a syntax error is found, and it receives one
argument.  For a parse error, the string is normally @{b}"parse error"@{ub}.

   If you define the macro @{b}YYERROR_VERBOSE@{ub} in the Bison declarations
section (see @{"The Bison Declarations Section" Link "Bison Declarations"}), then Bison provides a
more verbose and specific error message string instead of just plain
@{b}"parse error"@{ub}.  It doesn't matter what definition you use for
@{b}YYERROR_VERBOSE@{ub}, just whether you define it.

   The parser can detect one other kind of error: stack overflow.  This
happens when the input contains constructions that are very deeply
nested.  It isn't likely you will encounter this, since the Bison
parser extends its stack automatically up to a very large limit.  But
if overflow happens, @{b}yyparse@{ub} calls @{b}yyerror@{ub} in the usual fashion, except
that the argument string is @{b}"parser stack overflow"@{ub}.

   The following definition suffices in simple programs:

     yyerror (s)
          char *s;
     {
       fprintf (stderr, "%s\n", s);
     }

   After @{b}yyerror@{ub} returns to @{b}yyparse@{ub}, the latter will attempt error
recovery if you have written suitable error recovery grammar rules (see
@{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}).  If recovery is impossible, @{b}yyparse@{ub} will immediately
return 1.

   The variable @{b}yynerrs@{ub} contains the number of syntax errors
encountered so far.  Normally this variable is global; but if you
request a pure parser (see @{"A Pure (Reentrant) Parser" Link "Pure Decl"}) then it is a
local variable which only the actions can access.


@EndNode

@Node "Action Features" "Bison.guide/Action Features"
@Prev "Error Reporting"
@Toc "Interface"

Special Features for Use in Actions
===================================

   Here is a table of Bison constructs, variables and macros that are
useful in actions.

@{b}$$@{ub}
     Acts like a variable that contains the semantic value for the
     grouping made by the current rule.  See @{"Actions" Link "Actions"}.

@{b} $@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}
     Acts like a variable that contains the semantic value for the @{i}n@{ui}th
     component of the current rule.  See @{"Actions" Link "Actions"}.

@{b}$<@{i}typealt@{ui}>$@{ub}
     Like @{b}$$@{ub} but specifies alternative @{i}typealt@{ui} in the union specified
     by the @{b}%union@{ub} declaration.  See @{"Data Types of Values in Actions" Link "Action Types"}.

@{b}$<@{i}typealt@{ui}>@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}
     Like @{b} $@{i}n@{ui}@{ub} but specifies alternative @{i}typealt@{ui} in the union specified
     by the @{b}%union@{ub} declaration.  See @{"Data Types of Values in Actions" Link "Action Types"}.

@{b}YYABORT;@{ub}
     Return immediately from @{b}yyparse@{ub}, indicating failure.  See
     @{"The Parser Function yyparse" Link "Parser Function"}.

@{b}YYACCEPT;@{ub}
     Return immediately from @{b}yyparse@{ub}, indicating success.  See
     @{"The Parser Function yyparse" Link "Parser Function"}.

@{b}YYBACKUP (@{i}token@{ui}, @{i}value@{ui});@{ub}
     Unshift a token.  This macro is allowed only for rules that reduce
     a single value, and only when there is no look-ahead token.  It
     installs a look-ahead token with token type @{i}token@{ui} and semantic
     value @{i}value@{ui}; then it discards the value that was going to be
     reduced by this rule.

     If the macro is used when it is not valid, such as when there is a
     look-ahead token already, then it reports a syntax error with a
     message @{b}cannot back up@{ub} and performs ordinary error recovery.

     In either case, the rest of the action is not executed.

@{b}YYEMPTY@{ub}
     Value stored in @{b}yychar@{ub} when there is no look-ahead token.

@{b}YYERROR;@{ub}
     Cause an immediate syntax error.  This statement initiates error
     recovery just as if the parser itself had detected an error;
     however, it does not call @{b}yyerror@{ub}, and does not print any message.
     If you want to print an error message, call @{b}yyerror@{ub} explicitly
     before the @{b}YYERROR;@{ub} statement.  See @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b}YYRECOVERING@{ub}
     This macro stands for an expression that has the value 1 when the
     parser is recovering from a syntax error, and 0 the rest of the
     time.  See @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b}yychar@{ub}
     Variable containing the current look-ahead token.  (In a pure
     parser, this is actually a local variable within @{b}yyparse@{ub}.)  When
     there is no look-ahead token, the value @{b}YYEMPTY@{ub} is stored in the
     variable.  See @{"Look-Ahead Tokens" Link "Look-Ahead"}.

@{b}yyclearin;@{ub}
     Discard the current look-ahead token.  This is useful primarily in
     error rules.  See @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b}yyerrok;@{ub}
     Resume generating error messages immediately for subsequent syntax
     errors.  This is useful primarily in error rules.  See
     @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b} @@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}
     Acts like a structure variable containing information on the line
     numbers and column numbers of the @{i}n@{ui}th component of the current
     rule.  The structure has four members, like this:

          struct {
            int first_line, last_line;
            int first_column, last_column;
          };

     Thus, to get the starting line number of the third component, use @{b}
     @3.first_line@{ub}.

     In order for the members of this structure to contain valid
     information, you must make @{b}yylex@{ub} supply this information about
     each token.  If you need only certain members, then @{b}yylex@{ub} need
     only fill in those members.

     The use of this feature makes the parser noticeably slower.


@EndNode

@Node "Algorithm" "Bison.guide/Algorithm"
@Next "Error Recovery"
@Prev "Interface"
@Toc "Main"

The Bison Parser Algorithm
**************************

   As Bison reads tokens, it pushes them onto a stack along with their
semantic values.  The stack is called the @{i}parser stack@{ui}.  Pushing a
token is traditionally called @{i}shifting@{ui}.

   For example, suppose the infix calculator has read @{b}1 + 5 *@{ub}, with a @{b}3@{ub}
to come.  The stack will have four elements, one for each token that
was shifted.

   But the stack does not always have an element for each token read.
When the last @{i}n@{ui} tokens and groupings shifted match the components of a
grammar rule, they can be combined according to that rule.  This is
called @{i}reduction@{ui}.  Those tokens and groupings are replaced on the stack
by a single grouping whose symbol is the result (left hand side) of
that rule.  Running the rule's action is part of the process of
reduction, because this is what computes the semantic value of the
resulting grouping.

   For example, if the infix calculator's parser stack contains this:

     1 + 5 * 3

and the next input token is a newline character, then the last three
elements can be reduced to 15 via the rule:

     expr: expr '*' expr;

Then the stack contains just these three elements:

     1 + 15

At this point, another reduction can be made, resulting in the single
value 16.  Then the newline token can be shifted.

   The parser tries, by shifts and reductions, to reduce the entire
input down to a single grouping whose symbol is the grammar's
start-symbol (see @{"Languages and Context-Free Grammars" Link "Language and Grammar"}).

   This kind of parser is known in the literature as a bottom-up parser.


 @{" Look-Ahead " Link "Look-Ahead"}         Parser looks one token ahead when deciding what to do.
 @{" Shift-Reduce " Link "Shift-Reduce"}       Conflicts: when either shifting or reduction is valid.
