Bison Options
=============

   Bison supports both traditional single-letter options and mnemonic
long option names.  Long option names are indicated with @{b}-@{ub} instead of
@{b}-@{ub}.  Abbreviations for option names are allowed as long as they are
unique.  When a long option takes an argument, like @{b}-file-prefix@{ub},
connect the option name and the argument with @{b}=@{ub}.

   Here is a list of options that can be used with Bison, alphabetized
by short option.  It is followed by a cross key alphabetized by long
option.

@{b}-b @{i}file-prefix@{ui}@{ub}
@{b}-file-prefix=@{i}prefix@{ui}@{ub}
     Specify a prefix to use for all Bison output file names.  The
     names are chosen as if the input file were named @{b}@{i}prefix@{ui}.c@{ub}.

@{b}-d@{ub}
@{b}-defines@{ub}
     Write an extra output file containing macro definitions for the
     token type names defined in the grammar and the semantic value type
     @{b}YYSTYPE@{ub}, as well as a few @{b}extern@{ub} variable declarations.

     If the parser output file is named @{b}@{i}name@{ui}.c@{ub} then this file is named
     @{b}@{i}name@{ui}.h@{ub}.

     This output file is essential if you wish to put the definition of
     @{b}yylex@{ub} in a separate source file, because @{b}yylex@{ub} needs to be able to
     refer to token type codes and the variable @{b}yylval@{ub}.  See
     @{"Semantic Values of Tokens" Link "Token Values"}.

@{b}-l@{ub}
@{b}-no-lines@{ub}
     Don't put any @{b}#line@{ub} preprocessor commands in the parser file.
     Ordinarily Bison puts them in the parser file so that the C
     compiler and debuggers will associate errors with your source
     file, the grammar file.  This option causes them to associate
     errors with the parser file, treating it an independent source
     file in its own right.

@{b}-o @{i}outfile@{ui}@{ub}
@{b}-output-file=@{i}outfile@{ui}@{ub}
     Specify the name @{i}outfile@{ui} for the parser file.

     The other output files' names are constructed from @{i}outfile@{ui} as
     described under the @{b}-v@{ub} and @{b}-d@{ub} switches.

@{b}-p @{i}prefix@{ui}@{ub}
@{b}-name-prefix=@{i}prefix@{ui}@{ub}
     Rename the external symbols used in the parser so that they start
     with @{i}prefix@{ui} instead of @{b}yy@{ub}.  The precise list of symbols renamed is
     @{b}yyparse@{ub}, @{b}yylex@{ub}, @{b}yyerror@{ub}, @{b}yynerrs@{ub}, @{b}yylval@{ub}, @{b}yychar@{ub} and @{b}yydebug@{ub}.

     For example, if you use @{b}-p c@{ub}, the names become @{b}cparse@{ub}, @{b}clex@{ub}, and
     so on.

     See @{"Multiple Parsers in the Same Program" Link "Multiple Parsers"}.

@{b}-t@{ub}
@{b}-debug@{ub}
     Output a definition of the macro @{b}YYDEBUG@{ub} into the parser file, so
     that the debugging facilities are compiled.  See
     @{"Debugging Your Parser" Link "Debugging"}.

@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}-verbose@{ub}
     Write an extra output file containing verbose descriptions of the
     parser states and what is done for each type of look-ahead token in
     that state.

     This file also describes all the conflicts, both those resolved by
     operator precedence and the unresolved ones.

     The file's name is made by removing @{b}.tab.c@{ub} or @{b}.c@{ub} from the parser
     output file name, and adding @{b}.output@{ub} instead.

     Therefore, if the input file is @{b}foo.y@{ub}, then the parser file is
     called @{b}foo.tab.c@{ub} by default.  As a consequence, the verbose output
     file is called @{b}foo.output@{ub}.

@{b}-V@{ub}
@{b}-version@{ub}
     Print the version number of Bison and exit.

@{b}-h@{ub}
@{b}-help@{ub}
     Print a summary of the command-line options to Bison and exit.

@{b}-y@{ub}
@{b}-yacc@{ub}
@{b}-fixed-output-files@{ub}
     Equivalent to @{b}-o y.tab.c@{ub}; the parser output file is called
     @{b}y.tab.c@{ub}, and the other outputs are called @{b}y.output@{ub} and
     @{b}y.tab.h@{ub}.  The purpose of this switch is to imitate Yacc's
     output file name conventions.  Thus, the following shell script
     can substitute for Yacc:

          bison -y $*


@EndNode

