@Node "VMS Invocation" "Bison.guide/VMS Invocation"
@Prev "Option Cross Key"
@Toc "Invocation"

Invoking Bison under VMS
========================

   The command line syntax for Bison on VMS is a variant of the usual
Bison command syntax--adapted to fit VMS conventions.

   To find the VMS equivalent for any Bison option, start with the long
option, and substitute a @{b}/@{ub} for the leading @{b}-@{ub}, and substitute a @{b}_@{ub} for
each @{b}-@{ub} in the name of the long option.  For example, the following
invocation under VMS:

     bison /debug/name_prefix=bar foo.y

is equivalent to the following command under POSIX.

     bison --debug --name-prefix=bar foo.y

   The VMS file system does not permit filenames such as @{b}foo.tab.c@{ub}.  In
the above example, the output file would instead be named @{b}foo_tab.c@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Table of Symbols" "Bison.guide/Table of Symbols"
@Next "Glossary"
@Prev "Invocation"
@Toc "Main"

Bison Symbols
*************

@{b}error@{ub}
     A token name reserved for error recovery.  This token may be used
     in grammar rules so as to allow the Bison parser to recognize an
     error in the grammar without halting the process.  In effect, a
     sentence containing an error may be recognized as valid.  On a
     parse error, the token @{b}error@{ub} becomes the current look-ahead token.
     Actions corresponding to @{b}error@{ub} are then executed, and the
     look-ahead token is reset to the token that originally caused the
     violation.  See @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b}YYABORT@{ub}
     Macro to pretend that an unrecoverable syntax error has occurred,
     by making @{b}yyparse@{ub} return 1 immediately.  The error reporting
     function @{b}yyerror@{ub} is not called.  See @{"The Parser Function yyparse" Link "Parser Function"}.

@{b}YYACCEPT@{ub}
     Macro to pretend that a complete utterance of the language has been
     read, by making @{b}yyparse@{ub} return 0 immediately.  See
     @{"The Parser Function yyparse" Link "Parser Function"}.

@{b}YYBACKUP@{ub}
     Macro to discard a value from the parser stack and fake a
     look-ahead token.  See @{"Special Features for Use in Actions" Link "Action Features"}.

@{b}YYERROR@{ub}
     Macro to pretend that a syntax error has just been detected: call
     @{b}yyerror@{ub} and then perform normal error recovery if possible (see
     @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}), or (if recovery is impossible) make @{b}yyparse@{ub}
     return 1.  See @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b}YYERROR_VERBOSE@{ub}
     Macro that you define with @{b}#define@{ub} in the Bison declarations
     section to request verbose, specific error message strings when
     @{b}yyerror@{ub} is called.

@{b}YYINITDEPTH@{ub}
     Macro for specifying the initial size of the parser stack.  See
     @{"Stack Overflow" Link "Stack Overflow"}.

@{b}YYLEX_PARAM@{ub}
     Macro for specifying an extra argument (or list of extra
     arguments) for @{b}yyparse@{ub} to pass to @{b}yylex@{ub}.  See
     @{"Calling Conventions for Pure Parsers" Link "Pure Calling"}.

@{b}YYLTYPE@{ub}
     Macro for the data type of @{b}yylloc@{ub}; a structure with four members.
     See @{"Textual Positions of Tokens" Link "Token Positions"}.

@{b}YYMAXDEPTH@{ub}
     Macro for specifying the maximum size of the parser stack.  See
     @{"Stack Overflow" Link "Stack Overflow"}.

@{b}YYPARSE_PARAM@{ub}
     Macro for specifying the name of a parameter that @{b}yyparse@{ub} should
     accept.  See @{"Calling Conventions for Pure Parsers" Link "Pure Calling"}.

@{b}YYRECOVERING@{ub}
     Macro whose value indicates whether the parser is recovering from a
     syntax error.  See @{"Special Features for Use in Actions" Link "Action Features"}.

@{b}YYSTYPE@{ub}
     Macro for the data type of semantic values; @{b}int@{ub} by default.  See
     @{"Data Types of Semantic Values" Link "Value Type"}.

@{b}yychar@{ub}
     External integer variable that contains the integer value of the
     current look-ahead token.  (In a pure parser, it is a local
     variable within @{b}yyparse@{ub}.)  Error-recovery rule actions may examine
     this variable.  See @{"Special Features for Use in Actions" Link "Action Features"}.

@{b}yyclearin@{ub}
     Macro used in error-recovery rule actions.  It clears the previous
     look-ahead token.  See @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b}yydebug@{ub}
     External integer variable set to zero by default.  If @{b}yydebug@{ub} is
     given a nonzero value, the parser will output information on input
     symbols and parser action.  See @{"Debugging Your Parser" Link "Debugging"}.

@{b}yyerrok@{ub}
     Macro to cause parser to recover immediately to its normal mode
     after a parse error.  See @{"Error Recovery" Link "Error Recovery"}.

@{b}yyerror@{ub}
     User-supplied function to be called by @{b}yyparse@{ub} on error.  The
     function receives one argument, a pointer to a character string
     containing an error message.  See
     @{"The Error Reporting Function yyerror" Link "Error Reporting"}.

@{b}yylex@{ub}
     User-supplied lexical analyzer function, called with no arguments
     to get the next token.  See @{"The Lexical Analyzer Function yylex" Link "Lexical"}.

@{b}yylval@{ub}
     External variable in which @{b}yylex@{ub} should place the semantic value
     associated with a token.  (In a pure parser, it is a local
     variable within @{b}yyparse@{ub}, and its address is passed to @{b}yylex@{ub}.)  See
     @{"Semantic Values of Tokens" Link "Token Values"}.

@{b}yylloc@{ub}
     External variable in which @{b}yylex@{ub} should place the line and column
     numbers associated with a token.  (In a pure parser, it is a local
     variable within @{b}yyparse@{ub}, and its address is passed to @{b}yylex@{ub}.)  You
     can ignore this variable if you don't use the @{b} @@{ub} feature in the
     grammar actions.  See @{"Textual Positions of Tokens" Link "Token Positions"}.

@{b}yynerrs@{ub}
     Global variable which Bison increments each time there is a parse
     error.  (In a pure parser, it is a local variable within @{b}yyparse@{ub}.)
     See @{"The Error Reporting Function yyerror" Link "Error Reporting"}.

@{b}yyparse@{ub}
     The parser function produced by Bison; call this function to start
     parsing.  See @{"The Parser Function yyparse" Link "Parser Function"}.

@{b}%left@{ub}
     Bison declaration to assign left associativity to token(s).  See
     @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence Decl"}.

@{b}%nonassoc@{ub}
     Bison declaration to assign nonassociativity to token(s).  See
     @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence Decl"}.

@{b}%prec@{ub}
     Bison declaration to assign a precedence to a specific rule.  See
     @{"Context-Dependent Precedence" Link "Contextual Precedence"}.

@{b}%pure_parser@{ub}
     Bison declaration to request a pure (reentrant) parser.  See
     @{"A Pure (Reentrant) Parser" Link "Pure Decl"}.

@{b}%right@{ub}
     Bison declaration to assign right associativity to token(s).  See
     @{"Operator Precedence" Link "Precedence Decl"}.

@{b}%start@{ub}
     Bison declaration to specify the start symbol.  See
     @{"The Start-Symbol" Link "Start Decl"}.

@{b}%token@{ub}
     Bison declaration to declare token(s) without specifying
     precedence.  See @{"Token Type Names" Link "Token Decl"}.

@{b}%type@{ub}
     Bison declaration to declare nonterminals.  See
     @{"Nonterminal Symbols" Link "Type Decl"}.

@{b}%union@{ub}
     Bison declaration to specify several possible data types for
     semantic values.  See @{"The Collection of Value Types" Link "Union Decl"}.

   These are the punctuation and delimiters used in Bison input:

@{b}%%@{ub}
     Delimiter used to separate the grammar rule section from the Bison
     declarations section or the additional C code section.  See
     @{"The Overall Layout of a Bison Grammar" Link "Grammar Layout"}.

@{b} %{ %}@{ub}
     All code listed between @{b} %{@{ub} and @{b} %}@{ub} is copied directly to the
     output file uninterpreted.  Such code forms the "C declarations"
     section of the input file.  See @{"Outline of a Bison Grammar" Link "Grammar Outline"}.

@{b}/*...*/@{ub}
     Comment delimiters, as in C.

@{b}:@{ub}
     Separates a rule's result from its components.  See
     @{"Syntax of Grammar Rules" Link "Rules"}.

@{b};@{ub}
     Terminates a rule.  See @{"Syntax of Grammar Rules" Link "Rules"}.

@{b}|@{ub}
     Separates alternate rules for the same result nonterminal.  See
     @{"Syntax of Grammar Rules" Link "Rules"}.


@EndNode

